@Node "Overview" "wget.guide/Overview"
@Next "Invoking"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Overview
********

   GNU Wget is a freely available network utility to retrieve files from
the World Wide Web, using @{i}http@{ui} (Hyper Text Transfer Protocol) and @{i}ftp@{ui}
(File Transfer Protocol), the two most widely used Internet protocols.
It has many useful features to make downloading easier, some of them
being:

   @{b}*@{ub} Wget is non-interactive, which means it can work in the background,
     while the user is not logged on, so that you may start the program
     and log off, letting it do its work.  By contrast, most of the Web
     browsers require constant user's presence, which can be a great
     hindrance when transferring a lot of data.

   @{b}*@{ub} Wget is capable of descending recursively through the structure of
     @{i}html@{ui} documents and @{i}ftp@{ui} directory trees, making a local copy of
     the directory hierarchy similar to the one on the remote server.
     This feature can be used to mirror archives and home pages, or
     traverse the web in search of data, like a @{i}www@{ui} robot (See @{"Robots" Link "Robots"}).
     In that spirit, Wget understands the @{b}norobots@{ub} convention.

   @{b}*@{ub} File name wildcard matching and recursive mirroring of directories
     are available when retrieving via @{i}ftp@{ui}.  Wget can read the
     time-stamp information given by both @{i}http@{ui} and @{i}ftp@{ui} servers, and
     store it locally.  Thus Wget can see if the remote file has
     changed since last retrieval, and automatically retrieve the new
     version if it has.  This makes Wget suitable for mirroring of @{i}ftp@{ui}
     sites, as well as home pages.

   @{b}*@{ub} Wget works exceedingly well on slow or unstable connections,
     keeping getting the document until it is fully retrieved, or until
     a user-specified retry count is surpassed.  It will try to resume
     the download from the point of interruption, using @{b}REST@{ub} with @{i}ftp@{ui}
     and @{b}Range@{ub} with @{i}http@{ui} servers that support them.

   @{b}*@{ub} By default, Wget supports @{i}proxy@{ui} servers, which can lighten the
     network load, speed up retrieval and provide access behind
     firewalls.  However, if you are behind a firewall that requires
     that you use a socks style gateway, you can get the socks library
     and build wget with support for socks.  Wget also supports the
     passive @{i}ftp@{ui} downloading as an option.

   @{b}*@{ub} Builtin features offer mechanisms to tune which links you wish to
     follow (See @{"Following Links" Link "Following Links"}).

   @{b}*@{ub} The retrieval is conveniently traced with printing dots, each dot
     representing a fixed amount of data received (1KB by default).
     These representations can be customized to your preferences.

   @{b}*@{ub} Most of the features are fully configurable, either through
     command line options, or via the initialization file @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} (See
     @{"Startup File" Link "Startup File"}).  Wget allows you to define @{i}global@{ui} startup files
     (@{b}/usr/local/etc/wgetrc@{ub} by default) for site settings.

   @{b}*@{ub} Finally, GNU Wget is free software.  This means that everyone may
     use it, redistribute it and/or modify it under the terms of the
     GNU General Public License, as published by the Free Software
     Foundation (See @{"Copying" Link "Copying"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking" "wget.guide/Invoking"
@Next "Recursive Retrieval"
@Prev "Overview"
@Toc "Main"

Invoking
********

   By default, Wget is very simple to invoke.  The basic syntax is:

     wget [options] URL1 [URL2 ...]

   Wget will simply download all the @{i}url@{ui}s specified on the command
line.  URL is a @{i}Uniform Resource Locator@{ui}, as defined below.

   Be aware that @{b}ksh@{ub} and its descendants (like @{b}zsh@{ub}) kill off the
background processes during logout.  To prevent this, use @{b}nohup@{ub}, as
documented in system manuals.

   However, you may wish to change some of the default parameters of
Wget.  You can do it two ways: permanently, adding the appropriate
command to @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} (See @{"Startup File" Link "Startup File"}), or specifying it on the command
line.


 @{" URL Format                " Link "URL Format"}  What is considered a URL.
 @{" Option Syntax             " Link "Option Syntax"}  Syntax of options.
 @{" Basic Options             " Link "Basic Options"}  Basic command line arguments.
 @{" Advanced Options          " Link "Advanced Options"}  Advanced command line arguments.


@EndNode

@Node "URL Format" "wget.guide/URL Format"
@Next "Option Syntax"
@Prev "Invoking"
@Toc "Invoking"

URL Format
==========

   @{i}URL@{ui} is an acronym for Uniform Resource Locator.  Wget recognizes the
@{i}url@{ui} syntax as per @{i}rfc1738@{ui}.  This is the most widely used form
(square brackets denote optional parts):

     http://host[:port]/path
     ftp://host[:port]/path

   You can also encode your username and password within a @{i}url@{ui}:

     ftp://user:password@host/path
     http://user:password@host/path

   Either USER or PASSWORD, or both may be left out.  If you leave out
either the @{i}http@{ui} username or password, no authentication will be sent.
If you leave out the @{i}ftp@{ui} username, @{b}anonymous@{ub} will be used.  If you
leave out the @{i}ftp@{ui} password, your email address will be supplied as a
default password.(1)

   You can encode unsafe characters in a @{i}url@{ui} as @{b}%xy@{ub}, @{b}xy@{ub} being the
hexadecimal representation of the character's @{i}ascii@{ui} value.  Some common
unsafe characters include @{b}%@{ub} (quoted as @{b}%25@{ub}), @{b}:@{ub} (quoted as @{b}%3A@{ub}), and @{b} @@{ub}
(quoted as @{b}%40@{ub}).  Refer to @{i}rfc1738@{ui} for a comprehensive list of unsafe
characters.

   Two alternative variants of @{i}url@{ui} specification are also supported,
because of historical (hysterical?) reasons and their wide-spreadedness.

   @{i}ftp@{ui}-only syntax (supported by @{b}NcFTP@{ub}):
     host:/dir/file

   @{i}http@{ui}-only syntax (introduced by @{b}Netscape@{ub}):
     host[:port]/dir/file

   These two alternative forms are deprecated, and may cease being
supported in the future.

   If you do not understand the difference between these notations, or
do not know which one to use, just use the plain ordinary format you use
with your favorite browser, like @{b}Lynx@{ub} or @{b}Netscape@{ub}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  If you have a @{b}.netrc@{ub} file in your home directory, password will
also be searched for there.


@EndNode

@Node "Option Syntax" "wget.guide/Option Syntax"
@Next "Basic Options"
@Prev "URL Format"
@Toc "Invoking"

Option Syntax
=============

   Since Wget uses GNU getopts to process its arguments, every option
has a short form and a long form.  Long options are more convenient to
remember, but take time to type.  You may freely mix different option
styles, or specify options after the command-line arguments. Thus you
may write:

     wget -r --tries=10 http://fly.cc.fer.hr/ -o log

   The space between the option accepting an argument and the argument
may be omitted.  Instead @{b}-o log@{ub} you can write @{b}-olog@{ub}.

   You may put several options that do not require arguments together,
like:

     wget -drc URL

   This is a complete equivalent of:

     wget -d -r -c URL

   Since the options can be specified after the arguments, you may
terminate them with @{b}--@{ub}.  So the following will try to download @{i}url@{ui} @{b}-x@{ub},
reporting failure to @{b}log@{ub}:

     wget -o log -- -x

   The options that accept comma-separated lists all use the convention
that, when presented an empty list, it means to clear it.  This can be
useful to clear the @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} settings.  So, if your .wgetrc sets the
exclude_directories to @{b}/cgi-bin@{ub}, the following example will first reset
it, and then set it to exclude @{b}/~nobody@{ub} and @{b}/~somebody@{ub}.  You can also
clear the lists in @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} (See @{"Wgetrc Syntax" Link "Wgetrc Syntax"}).

     wget -X '' -X /~nobody,/~somebody


@EndNode

@Node "Basic Options" "wget.guide/Basic Options"
@Next "Advanced Options"
@Prev "Option Syntax"
@Toc "Invoking"

Basic Options
=============

   The command line arguments, sorted alphabetically.

@{b}-a LOGFILE@{ub}
@{b}--append-output=LOGFILE@{ub}
     Append to LOGFILE--the same as @{b}-o@{ub}, but appending to the LOGFILE
     (or creating a new one if the old does not exist) instead of
     overwriting the old log file.

@{b}-d@{ub}
@{b}--debug@{ub}
     Turn on debug output, meaning various information important to the
     developers of Wget if it does not work properly.  Your system
     administrator may have chosen to compile Wget without debug
     support.  In that case @{b}-d@{ub} will not work.  Please note that even if
     the program is compiled with debug support, it will @{i}not@{ui} print any
     debug info unless @{b}-d@{ub} is turned on explicitly.  See @{"Reporting Bugs" Link "Reporting Bugs"}
     for more information on how to send a bug report.

@{b}-h@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print a help screen. You will also get help if you do not supply
     command-line arguments.

@{b}-i FILE@{ub}
@{b}--input-file=FILE@{ub}
     Read @{i}url@{ui}s from FILE, in which case no @{i}url@{ui}s need to be on the
     command line.  If there are @{i}url@{ui}s both on the command line and in
     an input file, those on the command lines will be the first ones to
     be retrieved.  The FILE need not be an @{i}html@{ui} document (but no harm
     if it is)--it is enough if the @{i}url@{ui}s are just listed sequentially.

     However, if you specify @{b}--force-html@{ub}, the document will be
     regarded as @{b}html@{ub}.  In that case you may have problems with
     relative links, which you can solve either by adding @{b}<base
     href="URL">@{ub} to the documents or by specifying @{b}--base=URL@{ub} on the
     command line.

@{b}-l DEPTH@{ub}
@{b}--level=DEPTH@{ub}
     Specify recursion maximum depth level DEPTH (See
     @{"Recursive Retrieval" Link "Recursive Retrieval"}).  The default maximum depth is 5.

@{b}-nc@{ub}
@{b}--no-clobber@{ub}
     Do not clobber existing files when saving to directory hierarchy
     within recursive retrieval of several files. This option is
     @{i}extremely@{ui} useful when you wish to continue where you left off
     with retrieval of many files.  If the files have the @{b}.html@{ub} or
     (yuck) @{b}.htm@{ub} suffix, they will be loaded from the local disk, and
     parsed as if they have been retrieved from the Web.

@{b}-o LOGFILE@{ub}
@{b}--output-file=LOGFILE@{ub}
     Log all messages to LOGFILE, instead of standard output, which is
     the default.  If you do not wish the log output to be verbose, use
     @{b}-nv@{ub} (non-verbose).

@{b}-q@{ub}
@{b}--quiet@{ub}
     This option is the opposite of verbose, making Wget completely
     quiet.

@{b}-r@{ub}
@{b}--recursive@{ub}
     Turn on recursive retrieving (See @{"Recursive Retrieval" Link "Recursive Retrieval"}).

@{b}-t NUM@{ub}
@{b}--tries=NUM@{ub}
     Set number of retries to NUM.  Specify 0 or @{b}inf@{ub} for infinite
     retrying.

@{b}-V@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
     Display the version of Wget.

@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--verbose@{ub}
     Turn on verbose output, with all the available data.  The default
     output is verbose.


@EndNode

@Node "Advanced Options" "wget.guide/Advanced Options"
@Prev "Basic Options"
@Toc "Invoking"

Advanced Options
================

   The following table contains the alphabetically sorted list of the
@{i}advanced@{ui} command line arguments, for people familiar with basic
operating of Wget, wishing to change its default behavior.  Not for the
faint of heart.

@{b}-A ACCLIST --accept ACCLIST@{ub}
@{b}-R REJLIST --reject REJLIST@{ub}
     Specify comma-separated lists of file name suffices or patterns to
     accept or reject (See @{"Types of Files" Link "Types of Files"} for more details).

@{b}-c@{ub}
@{b}--continue@{ub}
     Continue retrieval of @{i}ftp@{ui} documents, from where it was left off by
     another program or a previous instance of Wget.  Thus you can
     write:

          wget -c ftp://sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk/ls-lR.Z

     If there is a file name @{b}ls-lR.Z@{ub} in the current directory, Wget
     will assume that it is the first portion of the remote file, and
     will require the server to continue the retrieval from an offset
     equal to the length of the local file.

     Note that you need not specify this option if all you want is Wget
     to continue retrieving where it left off when the connection is
     lost--Wget does this by default.  You need this option only when
     you want to continue retrieval of a file already halfway
     retrieved, saved by another @{i}ftp@{ui} client, or left by Wget being
     killed.

     Without @{b}-c@{ub}, the previous example would just begin to download the
     remote file to @{b}ls-lR.Z.1@{ub}.  The @{b}-c@{ub} option is also applicable for
     @{i}http@{ui} servers that support the @{b}Range@{ub} header.

@{b}-D DOMAIN-LIST@{ub}
@{b}--domains=DOMAIN-LIST@{ub}
     Set domains to be accepted and @{i}dns@{ui} looked-up, where DOMAIN-LIST is
     a comma-separated list.  Note that it does @{i}not@{ui} turn on @{b}-H@{ub}.  This
     option speeds things up, even if only one host is spanned (See
     @{"Domain Acceptance" Link "Domain Acceptance"}).

@{b}--delete-after@{ub}
     This option tells Wget to delete every single file it downloads,
     @{i}after@{ui} having done so.  It is useful for pre-fetching popular
     pages through @{i}proxy@{ui}, e.g.:

          wget -r -nd --delete-after http://whatever.com/~popular/page/

     The @{b}-r@{ub} option is to retrieve recursively, and @{b}-nd@{ub} not to create
     directories.

@{b}--dot-style=STYLE@{ub}
     Set the retrieval style to STYLE.  Wget traces the retrieval of
     each document by printing dots on the screen, each dot
     representing a fixed amount of retrieved data.  Any number of dots
     may be separated in a @{i}cluster@{ui}, to make counting easier.  This
     option allows you to choose one of the pre-defined styles,
     determining the number of bytes represented by a dot, the number
     of dots in a cluster, and the number of dots on the line.

     With the @{b}default@{ub} style each dot represents 1K, there are ten dots
     in a cluster and 50 dots in a line.  The @{b}binary@{ub} style has a more
     "computer"-like orientation--8K dots, 16-dots clusters and 64 dots
     per line (which makes for 512K lines).  The @{b}mega@{ub} style is suitable
     for downloading very large files--each dot represents 64K
     retrieved, there are eight dots in a cluster, and 48 dots on each
     line (so each line contains 3M).  The @{b}micro@{ub} style is exactly the
     reverse; it is suitable for downloading small files, with 128-byte
     dots, 8 dots per cluster, and 48 dots (6K) per line.

@{b}-e COMMAND@{ub}
@{b}--execute COMMAND@{ub}
     Execute COMMAND as if it were a part of @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} (See
     @{"Startup File" Link "Startup File"}).  A command thus invoked will be executed @{i}after@{ui} the
     commands in @{b}.wgetrc@{ub}, thus taking precedence over them.

@{b}--exclude-domains DOMAIN-LIST@{ub}
     Exclude the domains given in a comma-separated DOMAIN-LIST from
     @{i}dns@{ui}-lookup (See @{"Domain Acceptance" Link "Domain Acceptance"}).

@{b}--follow-ftp@{ub}
     Follow @{i}ftp@{ui} links from @{i}html@{ui} documents.  Without this option, Wget
     will ignore all the @{i}ftp@{ui} links.

@{b}-F@{ub}
@{b}--force-html@{ub}
     When input is read from a file, force it to be treated as an @{i}html@{ui}
     file.  This enables you to retrieve relative links from existing
     @{i}html@{ui} files on your local disk, by adding @{b}<base href="URL">@{ub} to
     @{i}html@{ui}, or using the @{b}--base@{ub} command-line option.

@{b}-g on/off@{ub}
@{b}--glob=on/off@{ub}
     Turn @{i}ftp@{ui} globbing on or off.  Globbing means you may use the
     shell-like special characters (@{i}wildcards@{ui}), like @{b}*@{ub}, @{b}?@{ub}, @{b}[@{ub} and @{b}]@{ub} to
     retrieve more than one file from the same directory at once, like:

          wget ftp://gnjilux.cc.fer.hr/*.msg

     By default, globbing will be turned on if the @{i}url@{ui} contains a
     globbing character.  This option may be used to turn globbing on
     or off permanently.

     You may have to quote the @{i}url@{ui} to protect it from being expanded by
     your shell.  Globbing makes Wget look for a directory listing,
     which is system-specific.  This is why it currently works only
     with Unix @{i}ftp@{ui} servers (and the ones emulating Unix @{b}ls@{ub} output).

@{b}--ignore-length@{ub}
     Unfortunately, some @{i}http@{ui} servers (@{i}cgi@{ui} programs, to be more
     precise) send out bogus @{b}Content-Length@{ub} headers, which makes Wget
     go wild, as it thinks not all the document was retrieved.  You can
     spot this syndrome if Wget retries getting the same document again
     and again, each time claiming that the (otherwise normal)
     connection has closed on the very same byte.

     With this option, Wget will ignore the @{b}Content-Length@{ub} header--as
     if it never existed.

@{b}--retr-symlinks@{ub}
     Retrieve symbolic links on @{i}ftp@{ui} sites as if they were plain files,
     i.e. don't just create links locally.

@{b}-H@{ub}
@{b}--span-hosts@{ub}
     Enable spanning across hosts when doing recursive retrieving (See
     @{"All Hosts" Link "All Hosts"}).

@{b}--header=ADDITIONAL-HEADER@{ub}
     Define an ADDITIONAL-HEADER to be passed to the @{i}http@{ui} servers.
     Headers must contain a @{b}:@{ub} preceded by one or more non-blank
     characters, and must not contain newlines.

     You may define more than one additional header by specifying
     @{b}--header@{ub} more than once.

          wget --header='Accept-Charset: iso-8859-2' \
               --header='Accept-Language: hr'        \
                 http://fly.cc.fer.hr/

     Specification of an empty string as the header value will clear all
     previous user-defined headers.

@{b}--http-user=USER@{ub}
@{b}--http-passwd=PASSWORD@{ub}
     Specify the username USER and password PASSWORD on an @{i}http@{ui} server.
     Wget will encode them using the @{b}basic@{ub} (insecure) @{i}www@{ui}
     authentication scheme.  You can also encode the username and
     password to the @{i}url@{ui} (See @{"URL Format" Link "URL Format"}).

     For more data about security issues with Wget, See
     @{"Security Considerations" Link "Security Considerations"}.

@{b}-I LIST@{ub}
@{b}--include-directories=LIST@{ub}
     Specify a comma-separated list of directories you wish to follow
     when downloading (See @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"} for more details)

@{b}-k@{ub}
@{b}--convert-links@{ub}
     Convert the non-relative links to relative ones locally.  Only the
     references to the documents actually downloaded will be converted;
     the rest will be left unchanged.

     Note that only at the end of the download can Wget know which links
     have been downloaded.  Because of that, much of the work done by
     `-k' will be performed at the end of the downloads.

@{b}-L@{ub}
@{b}--relative@{ub}
     Follow relative links only.  Useful for retrieving a specific home
     page without any distractions, not even those from the same hosts
     (See @{"Relative Links" Link "Relative Links"}).

@{b}-m@{ub}
@{b}--mirror@{ub}
     Turn on options suitable for mirroring.  This option turns on
     recursion and time-stamping, sets infinite recursion depth and
     keeps @{i}ftp@{ui} directory listings.  It is currently equivalent to @{b}-r -N
     -l0 -nr@{ub}.

@{b}-N@{ub}
@{b}--timestamping@{ub}
     Turn on time-stamping (See @{"Time-Stamping" Link "Time-Stamping"} for details).

@{b}-nd@{ub}
     Do not create a hierarchy of directories when retrieving
     recursively. With this option turned on, all files will get saved
     to the current directory, without clobbering (if a name shows up
     more than once, the filenames will get extensions @{b}.n@{ub}).

@{b}-nH@{ub}
     Disable generation of host-prefixed directories.  By default,
     invoking Wget with @{b}-r http://fly.cc.fer.hr/@{ub} will create a
     structure of directories beginning with @{b}fly.cc.fer.hr/@{ub}.  This
     option disables such behavior.

@{b}-nh@{ub}
     Disable the time-consuming @{i}dns@{ui} lookup of almost all hosts (See
     @{"Host Checking" Link "Host Checking"}).

@{b}-np@{ub}
@{b}--no-parent@{ub}
     Do not ever ascend to the parent directory when retrieving
     recursively.  This is a useful option, since it guarantees that
     only the files @{i}below@{ui} a certain hierarchy will be downloaded.  See
     @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"} for more details.

@{b}-nr@{ub}
     Do not remove the @{b}.listing@{ub} files generated by @{i}ftp@{ui}.  This is useful
     when running a mirror to see the remote file list.  It can also be
     used for debugging purposes.

@{b}-nv@{ub}
     Non-verbose output--turn off verbose without being completely quiet
     (use @{b}-q@{ub} for that), which means that error messages and basic
     information still get printed.

@{b}-O FILE@{ub}
@{b}--output-document=FILE@{ub}
     The documents will not be written to the appropriate files, but
     all will be appended to a unique file specified by this option.
     The number of tries will be set to 1 automatically.  If the FILE
     is @{b}-@{ub}, the documents will be written to standard output, and @{b}--quiet@{ub}
     will be turned on.  This option is useful for making Wget a part of
     pipelines (See @{"Advanced Usage" Link "Advanced Usage"}).

     Be careful, however, since setting @{b}--quiet@{ub} turns off all the
     useful diagnostics Wget can otherwise give.  This option is
     usually a bad choice, as it disables a great number of Wget
     features, e.g. recursive retrieval.

@{b}--passive-ftp@{ub}
     Use the @{i}passive@{ui} @{i}ftp@{ui} retrieval scheme, in which the client
     initiates the data connection.  This is sometimes required for @{i}ftp@{ui}
     to work behind firewalls.

@{b}-P PREFIX@{ub}
@{b}--directory-prefix=PREFIX@{ub}
     Set directory prefix to PREFIX.  The @{i}directory prefix@{ui} is the
     directory where all other files and subdirectories will be saved
     to, i.e. the top of the retrieval tree.  The default is @{b}.@{ub} (the
     current directory).

@{b}--proxy-user=USER@{ub}
@{b}--proxy-passwd=PASSWORD@{ub}
     Specify the username USER and password PASSWORD for authentication
     on a @{i}proxy@{ui} server.  Like with @{b}--http-user@{ub} and @{b}--http-passwd@{ub}, Wget
     will encode them using the @{b}basic@{ub} authentication scheme.

@{b}-Q QUOTA@{ub}
@{b}--quota=QUOTA@{ub}
     Specify download quota for automatic retrievals.  The value can be
     specified in bytes (default), kilobytes (with @{b}k@{ub} suffix), or
     megabytes (with @{b}m@{ub} suffix).

     Note that quota will never affect downloading a single file.  So
     if you specify @{b}wget -Q10k ftp://wuarchive.wustl.edu/ls-lR.gz@{ub}, all
     of the @{b}ls-lR.gz@{ub} will be downloaded.  The same goes even when
     several @{i}url@{ui}s are specified on the command-line.  However, quota is
     respected when retrieving either recursively, or from an input
     file.  Thus you may safely type @{b}wget -Q2m -i sites@{ub}--download will
     be aborted when the quota is exceeded.

     Setting quota to 0 or to @{b}inf@{ub} unlimits the download quota.

@{b}-S@{ub}
@{b}--server-response@{ub}
     Print the headers sent by @{i}http@{ui} servers and responses sent by @{i}ftp@{ui}
     servers.

@{b}-s@{ub}
@{b}--save-headers@{ub}
     Save the headers sent by the @{i}http@{ui} server to the file, preceding the
     actual contents, with an empty line as the separator.

@{b}--spider@{ub}
     When invoked with this option, Wget will behave as a Web @{i}spider@{ui},
     which means that it will not download the pages, just check that
     they are there.  You can use it to check your bookmarks, e.g. with:

          wget --spider --force-html -i bookmarks.html

     This feature needs much more work for Wget to get close to the
     functionality of real @{i}www@{ui} spiders.

@{b}-T seconds@{ub}
@{b}--timeout=SECONDS@{ub}
     Set the read timeout to SECONDS seconds.  Whenever a network read
     is issued, the file descriptor is checked for a timeout, which
     could otherwise leave a pending connection (uninterrupted read).
     The default timeout is 900 seconds (fifteen minutes).  Setting
     timeout to 0 will disable checking for timeouts.

     Please do not lower the default timeout value with this option
     unless you know what you are doing.

@{b}-w SECONDS@{ub}
@{b}--wait=SECONDS@{ub}
     Wait the specified number of seconds between the retrievals.  Use
     of this option is recommended, as it lightens the server load by
     making the requests less frequent.

@{b}-X LIST@{ub}
@{b}--exclude-directories=LIST@{ub}
     Specify a comma-separated list of directories you wish to exclude
     from download (See @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"} for more details).

@{b}-x@{ub}
     The opposite of @{b}-nd@{ub}--create a hierarchy of directories, even if
     one would not have been created otherwise.  E.g. @{b}wget -x
     http://fly.cc.fer.hr/robots.txt@{ub} will save the downloaded file to
     @{b}fly.cc.fer.hr/robots.txt@{ub}.

@{b}-Y on/off@{ub}
@{b}--proxy=on/off@{ub}
     Turn @{i}proxy@{ui} support on or off. The proxy is on by default if the
     appropriate environmental variable is defined.


@EndNode

@Node "Recursive Retrieval" "wget.guide/Recursive Retrieval"
@Next "Following Links"
@Prev "Invoking"
@Toc "Main"

Recursive Retrieval
*******************

   GNU Wget is capable of traversing parts of the Web (or a single @{i}http@{ui}
or @{i}ftp@{ui} server), depth-first following links and directory structure.
This is called @{i}recursive@{ui} retrieving, or @{i}recursion@{ui}.

   With @{i}http@{ui} @{i}url@{ui}s, Wget retrieves and parses the @{i}html@{ui} from the given
@{i}url@{ui}, documents, retrieving the files the @{i}html@{ui} document was
referring to, through markups like @{b}href@{ub}, or @{b}src@{ub}.  If the freshly
downloaded file is also of type @{b}text/html@{ub}, it will be parsed and
followed further.

   The maximum "depth" to which the retrieval may descend is specified
with the @{b}-l@{ub} option (the default maximum depth is five layers).  See
@{"Basic Options" Link "Basic Options"}.

   When retrieving an @{i}ftp@{ui} @{i}url@{ui} recursively, Wget will retrieve all the
data from the given directory tree (including the subdirectories up to
the specified depth) on the remote server, creating its mirror image
locally.  @{i}ftp@{ui} retrieval is also limited by the @{b}dept@{ub} parameter.

   By default, Wget will create a local directory tree, corresponding to
the one found on the remote server.

   Recursive retrieving can find a number of applications, the most
important of which is mirroring.  It is also useful for @{i}www@{ui}
presentations, and any other opportunities where slow network
connections should be bypassed by storing the files locally.

   You should be warned that invoking recursion may cause grave
overloading on your system, because of the fast exchange of data
through the network; all of this may hamper other users' work.  The
same stands for the foreign server you are mirroring--the more requests
it gets in a rows, the greater is its load.

   Careless retrieving can also fill your file system unctrollably,
which can grind the machine to a halt.

   The load can be minimized by lowering the maximum recursion level
(@{b}-l@{ub}) and/or by lowering the number of retries (@{b}-t@{ub}).  You may
also consider using the @{b}-w@{ub} option to slow down your requests to the
remote servers, as well as the numerous options to narrow the number of
followed links (See @{"Following Links" Link "Following Links"}).

   Recursive retrieval is a good thing when used properly.  Please take
all precautions not to wreak havoc through carelessness.


@EndNode

@Node "Following Links" "wget.guide/Following Links"
@Next "Time-Stamping"
@Prev "Recursive Retrieval"
@Toc "Main"

Following Links
***************

   When retrieving recursively, one does not wish to retrieve the loads
of unnecessary data.  Most of the time the users bear in mind exactly
what they want to download, and want Wget to follow only specific links.

   For example, if you wish to download the music archive from
@{b}fly.cc.fer.hr@{ub}, you will not want to download all the home pages
that happen to be referenced by an obscure part of the archive.

   Wget possesses several mechanisms that allows you to fine-tune which
links it will follow.


 @{" Relative Links            " Link "Relative Links"}  Follow relative links only.
 @{" Host Checking             " Link "Host Checking"}  Follow links on the same host.
 @{" Domain Acceptance         " Link "Domain Acceptance"}  Check on a list of domains.
 @{" All Hosts                 " Link "All Hosts"}  No host restrictions.
 @{" Types of Files            " Link "Types of Files"}  Getting only certain files.
 @{" Directory-Based Limits    " Link "Directory-Based Limits"}  Getting only certain directories.
 @{" FTP Links                 " Link "FTP Links"}  Following FTP links.


@EndNode

@Node "Relative Links" "wget.guide/Relative Links"
@Next "Host Checking"
@Prev "Following Links"
@Toc "Following Links"

Relative Links
==============

   When only relative links are followed (option @{b}-L@{ub}), recursive
retrieving will never span hosts.  No time-expensive @{i}dns@{ui}-lookups will
be performed, and the process will be very fast, with the minimum
strain of the network.  This will suit your needs often, especially when
mirroring the output of various @{b}x2html@{ub} converters, since they generally
output relative links.


@EndNode

@Node "Host Checking" "wget.guide/Host Checking"
@Next "Domain Acceptance"
@Prev "Relative Links"
@Toc "Following Links"

Host Checking
=============

   The drawback of following the relative links solely is that humans
often tend to mix them with absolute links to the very same host, and
the very same page.  In this mode (which is the default mode for
following links) all @{i}url@{ui}s the that refer to the same host will be
retrieved.

   The problem with this option are the aliases of the hosts and
domains.  Thus there is no way for Wget to know that @{b}regoc.srce.hr@{ub} and
@{b}www.srce.hr@{ub} are the same host, or that @{b}fly.cc.fer.hr@{ub} is the same as
@{b}fly.cc.etf.hr@{ub}.  Whenever an absolute link is encountered, the host
is @{i}dns@{ui}-looked-up with @{b}gethostbyname@{ub} to check whether we are maybe
dealing with the same hosts.  Although the results of @{b}gethostbyname@{ub} are
cached, it is still a great slowdown, e.g. when dealing with large
indices of home pages on different hosts (because each of the hosts
must be and @{i}dns@{ui}-resolved to see whether it just @{i}might@{ui} an alias of the
starting host).

   To avoid the overhead you may use @{b}-nh@{ub}, which will turn off
@{i}dns@{ui}-resolving and make Wget compare hosts literally.  This will
make things run much faster, but also much less reliable (e.g.
@{b}www.srce.hr@{ub} and @{b}regoc.srce.hr@{ub} will be flagged as different hosts).

   Note that @{i}http/1.1@{ui} allows one IP address to support several virtual
servers, each of them with its own root; this feature is also used by
many @{i}http/1.0@{ui} servers.  Such "servers" are then distinguished by their
hostnames (all of which point to the same IP address); for this to
work, a client must send a @{b}Host@{ub} header, which is what Wget does.
However, in that case Wget @{i}must not@{ui} try to divine a host's "real"
address, nor try to use the same hostname for each access, i.e. @{b}-nh@{ub}
must be turned on.

   In other words, the @{b}-nh@{ub} option must be used to enabling the
retrieval from virtual servers distinguished by their hostnames.  As the
number of such server setups grow, the behavior of @{b}-nh@{ub} may become the
default in the future.


@EndNode

@Node "Domain Acceptance" "wget.guide/Domain Acceptance"
@Next "All Hosts"
@Prev "Host Checking"
@Toc "Following Links"

Domain Acceptance
=================

   With the @{b}-D@{ub} option you may specify the domains that will be
followed.  The hosts the domain of which is not in this list will not be
@{i}dns@{ui}-resolved.  Thus you can specify @{b}-Dmit.edu@{ub} just to make sure
that @{i}nothing outside of @{i}mit@{ui} gets looked up@{ui}.  This is very important and
useful.  It also means that @{b}-D@{ub} does @{i}not@{ui} imply @{b}-H@{ub} (span all hosts),
which must be specified explicitly.  Feel free to use this options
since it will speed things up, with almost all the reliability of
checking for all hosts.  Thus you could invoke

     wget -r -D.hr http://fly.cc.fer.hr/

   to make sure that only the hosts in @{b}.hr@{ub} domain get @{i}dns@{ui}-looked-up for
being equal to @{b}fly.cc.fer.hr@{ub}.  So @{b}fly.cc.etf.hr@{ub} will be checked (only
once!) and found equal, but @{b}www.gnu.ai.mit.edu@{ub} will not even be checked.

   Of course, domain acceptance can be used to limit the retrieval to
particular domains with spanning of hosts in them, but then you must
specify @{b}-H@{ub} explicitly.  E.g.:

     wget -r -H -Dmit.edu,stanford.edu http://www.mit.edu/

   will start with @{b}http://www.mit.edu/@{ub}, following links across @{i}mit@{ui} and
Stanford.

   If there are domains you want to exclude specifically, you can do it
with @{b}--exclude-domains@{ub}, which accepts the same type of arguments of @{b}-D@{ub},
but will @{i}exclude@{ui} all the listed domains.  For example, if you want to
download all the hosts from @{b}foo.edu@{ub} domain, with the exception of
@{b}sunsite.foo.edu@{ub}, you can do it like this:

     wget -rH -Dfoo.edu --exclude-domains sunsite.foo.edu http://www.foo.edu/


@EndNode

@Node "All Hosts" "wget.guide/All Hosts"
@Next "Types of Files"
@Prev "Domain Acceptance"
@Toc "Following Links"

All Hosts
=========

   When @{b}-H@{ub} is specified without @{b}-D@{ub}, all hosts are freely spanned.
There are no restrictions whatsoever as to what part of the net Wget
will go to fetch documents, other than maximum retrieval depth.  If a
page references @{b}www.yahoo.com@{ub}, so be it.  Such an option is rarely
useful for itself.


@EndNode

@Node "Types of Files" "wget.guide/Types of Files"
@Next "Directory-Based Limits"
@Prev "All Hosts"
@Toc "Following Links"

Types of Files
==============

   When downloading material from the web, you will often want to
restrict the retrieval to only certain file types.  For example, if you
are interested in downloading @{i}gifs@{ui}, you will not be overjoyed to get
loads of Postscript documents, and vice versa.

   Wget offers two options to deal with this problem.  Each option
description lists a short name, a long name, and the equivalent command
in @{b}.wgetrc@{ub}.

@{b}-A ACCLIST@{ub}
@{b}--accept ACCLIST@{ub}
@{b}accept = ACCLIST@{ub}
     The argument to @{b}--accept@{ub} option is a list of file suffixes or
     patterns that Wget will download during recursive retrieval.  A
     suffix is the ending part of a file, and consists of "normal"
     letters, e.g. @{b}gif@{ub} or @{b}.jpg@{ub}.  A matching pattern contains shell-like
     wildcards, e.g. @{b}books*@{ub} or @{b}zelazny*196[0-9]*@{ub}.

     So, specifying @{b}wget -A gif,jpg@{ub} will make Wget download only the
     files ending with @{b}gif@{ub} or @{b}jpg@{ub}, i.e. @{i}gif@{ui}s and @{i}jpeg@{ui}s.  On the other
     hand, @{b}wget -A "zelazny*196[0-9]*"@{ub} will download only files
     beginning with @{b}zelazny@{ub} and containing numbers from 1960 to 1969
     anywhere within.  Look up the manual of your shell for a
     description of how pattern matching works.

     Of course, any number of suffixes and patterns can be combined
     into a comma-separated list, and given as an argument to @{b}-A@{ub}.

@{b}-R REJLIST@{ub}
@{b}--reject REJLIST@{ub}
@{b}reject = REJLIST@{ub}
     The @{b}--reject@{ub} option works the same way as @{b}--accept@{ub}, only its logic
     is the reverse; Wget will download all files @{i}except@{ui} the ones
     matching the suffixes (or patterns) in the list.

     So, if you want to download a whole page except for the cumbersome
     @{i}mpeg@{ui}s and @{i}.au@{ui} files, you can use @{b}wget -R mpg,mpeg,au@{ub}.
     Analogously, to download all files except the ones beginning with
     @{b}bjork@{ub}, use @{b}wget -R "bjork*"@{ub}.  The quotes are to prevent
     expansion by the shell.

   The @{b}-A@{ub} and @{b}-R@{ub} options may be combined to achieve even better
fine-tuning of which files to retrieve.  E.g. @{b}wget -A "*zelazny*" -R
.ps@{ub} will download all the files having @{b}zelazny@{ub} as a part of their
name, but @{i}not@{ui} the postscript files.

   Note that these two options do not affect the downloading of @{i}html@{ui}
files; Wget must load all the @{i}html@{ui}s to know where to go at
all--recursive retrieval would make no sense otherwise.


@EndNode

@Node "Directory-Based Limits" "wget.guide/Directory-Based Limits"
@Next "FTP Links"
@Prev "Types of Files"
@Toc "Following Links"

Directory-Based Limits
======================

   Regardless of other link-following facilities, it is often useful to
place the restriction of what files to retrieve based on the directories
those files are placed in.  There can be many reasons for this--the
home pages may be organized in a reasonable directory structure; or some
directories may contain useless information, e.g. @{b}/cgi-bin@{ub} or @{b}/dev@{ub}
directories.

   Wget offers three different options to deal with this requirement.
Each option description lists a short name, a long name, and the
equivalent command in @{b}.wgetrc@{ub}.

@{b}-I LIST@{ub}
@{b}--include LIST@{ub}
@{b}include_directories = LIST@{ub}
     @{b}-I@{ub} option accepts a comma-separated list of directories included
     in the retrieval.  Any other directories will simply be ignored.
     The directories are absolute paths.

     So, if you wish to download from @{b}http://host/people/bozo/@{ub}
     following only links to bozo's colleagues in the @{b}/people@{ub} directory
     and the bogus scripts in @{b}/cgi-bin@{ub}, you can specify:

          wget -I /people,/cgi-bin http://host/people/bozo/

@{b}-X LIST@{ub}
@{b}--exclude LIST@{ub}
@{b}exclude_directories = LIST@{ub}
     @{b}-X@{ub} option is exactly the reverse of @{b}-I@{ub}--this is a list of
     directories @{i}excluded@{ui} from the download.  E.g. if you do not want
     Wget to download things from @{b}/cgi-bin@{ub} directory, specify @{b}-X
     /cgi-bin@{ub} on the command line.

     The same as with @{b}-A@{ub}/@{b}-R@{ub}, these two options can be combined to get a
     better fine-tuning of downloading subdirectories.  E.g. if you
     want to load all the files from @{b}/pub@{ub} hierarchy except for
     @{b}/pub/worthless@{ub}, specify @{b}-I/pub -X/pub/worthless@{ub}.

@{b}-np@{ub}
@{b}--no-parent@{ub}
@{b}no_parent = on@{ub}
     The simplest, and often very useful way of limiting directories is
     disallowing retrieval of the links that refer to the hierarchy
     @{i}upper@{ui} than the beginning directory, i.e. disallowing ascent to
     the parent directory/directories.

     The @{b}--no-parent@{ub} option (short @{b}-np@{ub}) is useful in this case.  Using
     it guarantees that you will never leave the existing hierarchy.
     Supposing you issue Wget with:

          wget -r --no-parent http://somehost/~luzer/my-archive/

     You may rest assured that none of the references to
     @{b}/~his-girls-homepage/@{ub} or @{b}/~luzer/all-my-mpegs/@{ub} will be
     followed.  Only the archive you are interested in will be
     downloaded.  Essentially, @{b}--no-parent@{ub} is similar to
     @{b}-I/~luzer/my-archive@{ub}, only it handles redirections in a more
     intelligent fashion.


@EndNode

@Node "FTP Links" "wget.guide/FTP Links"
@Prev "Directory-Based Limits"
@Toc "Following Links"

Following FTP Links
===================

   The rules for @{i}ftp@{ui} are somewhat specific, as it is necessary for them
to be.  @{i}ftp@{ui} links in @{i}html@{ui} documents are often included for purposes of
reference, and it is often inconvenient to download them by default.

   To have @{i}ftp@{ui} links followed from @{i}html@{ui} documents, you need to specify
the @{b}--follow-ftp@{ub} option.  Having done that, @{i}ftp@{ui} links will span hosts
regardless of @{b}-H@{ub} setting.  This is logical, as @{i}ftp@{ui} links rarely point
to the same host where the @{i}http@{ui} server resides.  For similar reasons,
the @{b}-L@{ub} options has no effect on such downloads.  On the other hand,
domain acceptance (@{b}-D@{ub}) and suffix rules (@{b}-A@{ub} and @{b}-R@{ub}) apply normally.

   Also note that followed links to @{i}ftp@{ui} directories will not be
retrieved recursively further.


@EndNode

@Node "Time-Stamping" "wget.guide/Time-Stamping"
@Next "Startup File"
@Prev "Following Links"
@Toc "Main"

Time-Stamping
*************

   One of the most important aspects of mirroring information from the
Internet is updating your archives.

   Downloading the whole archive again and again, just to replace a few
changed files is expensive, both in terms of wasted bandwidth and money,
and the time to do the update.  This is why all the mirroring tools
offer the option of incremental updating.

   Such an updating mechanism means that the remote server is scanned in
search of @{i}new@{ui} files.  Only those new files will be downloaded in the
place of the old ones.

   A file is considered new if one of these two conditions are met:

  1. A file of that name does not already exist locally.

  2. A file of that name does exist, but the remote file was modified
     more recently than the local file.

   To implement this, the program needs to be aware of the time of last
modification of both remote and local files.  Such information are
called the @{i}time-stamps@{ui}.

   The time-stamping in GNU Wget is turned on using @{b}--timestamping@{ub} (@{b}-N@{ub})
option, or through @{b}timestamping = on@{ub} directive in @{b}.wgetrc@{ub}.  With this
option, for each file it intends to download, Wget will check whether a
local file of the same name exists.  If it does, and the remote file is
older, Wget will not download it.

   If the local file does not exist, or the sizes of the files do not
match, Wget will download the remote file no matter what the time-stamps
say.


 @{" Time-Stamping Usage       " Link "Time-Stamping Usage"}  
 @{" HTTP Time-Stamping Internals " Link "HTTP Time-Stamping Internals"}  
 @{" FTP Time-Stamping Internals " Link "FTP Time-Stamping Internals"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Time-Stamping Usage" "wget.guide/Time-Stamping Usage"
@Next "HTTP Time-Stamping Internals"
@Prev "Time-Stamping"
@Toc "Time-Stamping"

Time-Stamping Usage
===================

   The usage of time-stamping is simple.  Say you would like to
download a file so that it keeps its date of modification.

     wget -S http://www.gnu.ai.mit.edu/

   A simple @{b}ls -l@{ub} shows that the time stamp on the local file equals
the state of the @{b}Last-Modified@{ub} header, as returned by the server.  As
you can see, the time-stamping info is preserved locally, even without
@{b}-N@{ub}.

   Several days later, you would like Wget to check if the remote file
has changed, and download it if it has.

     wget -N http://www.gnu.ai.mit.edu/

   Wget will ask the server for the last-modified date.  If the local
file is newer, the remote file will not be re-fetched.  However, if the
remote file is more recent, Wget will proceed fetching it normally.

   The same goes for @{i}ftp@{ui}.  For example:

     wget ftp://ftp.ifi.uio.no/pub/emacs/gnus/*

   @{b}ls@{ub} will show that the timestamps are set according to the state on
the remote server.  Reissuing the command with @{b}-N@{ub} will make Wget
re-fetch @{i}only@{ui} the files that have been modified.

   In both @{i}http@{ui} and @{i}ftp@{ui} retrieval Wget will time-stamp the local file
correctly (with or without @{b}-N@{ub}) if it gets the stamps, i.e. gets the
directory listing for @{i}ftp@{ui} or the @{b}Last-Modified@{ub} header for @{i}http@{ui}.

   If you wished to mirror the GNU archive every week, you would use the
following command every week:

     wget --timestamping -r ftp://prep.ai.mit.edu/pub/gnu/


@EndNode

@Node "HTTP Time-Stamping Internals" "wget.guide/HTTP Time-Stamping Internals"
@Next "FTP Time-Stamping Internals"
@Prev "Time-Stamping Usage"
@Toc "Time-Stamping"

HTTP Time-Stamping Internals
============================

   Time-stamping in @{i}http@{ui} is implemented by checking of the
@{b}Last-Modified@{ub} header.  If you wish to retrieve the file
@{b}foo.html@{ub} through @{i}http@{ui}, Wget will check whether @{b}foo.html@{ub} exists
locally.  If it doesn't, @{b}foo.html@{ub} will be retrieved unconditionally.

   If the file does exist locally, Wget will first check its local
time-stamp (similar to the way @{b}ls -l@{ub} checks it), and then send a @{b}HEAD@{ub}
request to the remote server, demanding the information on the remote
file.

   The @{b}Last-Modified@{ub} header is examined to find which file was modified
more recently (which makes it "newer").  If the remote file is newer,
it will be downloaded; if it is older, Wget will give up.(1)

   Arguably, @{i}http@{ui} time-stamping should be implemented using the
@{b}If-Modified-Since@{ub} request.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  As an additional check, Wget will look at the @{b}Content-Length@{ub}
header, and compare the sizes; if they are not the same, the remote
file will be downloaded no matter what the time-stamp says.


@EndNode

@Node "FTP Time-Stamping Internals" "wget.guide/FTP Time-Stamping Internals"
@Prev "HTTP Time-Stamping Internals"
@Toc "Time-Stamping"

FTP Time-Stamping Internals
===========================

   In theory, @{i}ftp@{ui} time-stamping works much the same as @{i}http@{ui}, only @{i}ftp@{ui}
has no headers--time-stamps must be received from the directory
listings.

   For each directory files must be retrieved from, Wget will use the
@{b}LIST@{ub} command to get the listing.  It will try to analyze the
listing, assuming that it is a Unix @{b}ls -l@{ub} listing, and extract the
time-stamps.  The rest is exactly the same as for @{i}http@{ui}.

   Assumption that every directory listing is a Unix-style listing may
sound extremely constraining, but in practice it is not, as many
non-Unix @{i}ftp@{ui} servers use the Unixoid listing format because most (all?)
of the clients understand it.  Bear in mind that @{i}rfc959@{ui} defines no
standard way to get a file list, let alone the time-stamps.  We can
only hope that a future standard will define this.

   Another non-standard solution includes the use of @{b}MDTM@{ub} command that
is supported by some @{i}ftp@{ui} servers (including the popular @{b}wu-ftpd@{ub}), which
returns the exact time of the specified file.  Wget may support this
command in the future.


@EndNode

@Node "Startup File" "wget.guide/Startup File"
@Next "Examples"
@Prev "Time-Stamping"
@Toc "Main"

Startup File
************

   Once you know how to change default settings of Wget through command
line arguments, you may wish to make some of those settings permanent.
You can do that in a convenient way by creating the Wget startup
file--@{b}.wgetrc@{ub}.

   Besides @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} is the "main" initialization file, it is convenient
to have a special facility for storing passwords.  Thus Wget reads and
interprets the contents of @{b}$HOME/.netrc@{ub}, if it finds it.  You can find
@{b}.netrc@{ub} format in your system manuals.

   Wget reads @{b}.wgetrc@{ub} upon startup, recognizing a limited set of
commands.


 @{" Wgetrc Location           " Link "Wgetrc Location"}  Location of various wgetrc files.
 @{" Wgetrc Syntax             " Link "Wgetrc Syntax"}  Syntax of wgetrc.
 @{" Wgetrc Commands           " Link "Wgetrc Commands"}  List of available commands.
 @{" Sample Wgetrc             " Link "Sample Wgetrc"}  A wgetrc example.


@EndNode

@Node "Wgetrc Location" "wget.guide/Wgetrc Location"
@Next "Wgetrc Syntax"
@Prev "Startup File"
@Toc "Startup File"

Wgetrc Location
===============

   When initializing, Wget will look for a @{i}global@{ui} startup file,
@{b}/usr/local/etc/wgetrc@{ub} by default (or some prefix other than
@{b}/usr/local@{ub}, if Wget was not installed there) and read commands from
there, if it exists.

   Then it will look for the user's file.  If the environmental variable
@{b}WGETRC@{ub} is set, Wget will try to load that file.  Failing that, no
further attempts will be made.

   If @{b}WGETRC@{ub} is not set, Wget will try to load @{b}$HOME/.wgetrc@{ub}.

   The fact that user's settings are loaded after the system-wide ones
means that in case of collision user's wgetrc @{i}overrides@{ui} the system-wide
wgetrc (in @{b}/usr/local/etc/wgetrc@{ub} by default).  Fascist admins, away!


@EndNode

@Node "Wgetrc Syntax" "wget.guide/Wgetrc Syntax"
@Next "Wgetrc Commands"
@Prev "Wgetrc Location"
@Toc "Startup File"

Wgetrc Syntax
=============

   The syntax of a wgetrc command is simple:

     variable = value

   The @{i}variable@{ui} will also be called @{i}command@{ui}.  Valid @{i}values@{ui} are
different for different commands.

   The commands are case-insensitive and underscore-insensitive.  Thus
@{b}DIr__PrefiX@{ub} is the same as @{b}dirprefix@{ub}.  Empty lines, lines beginning
with @{b}#@{ub} and lines containing white-space only are discarded.

   Commands that expect a comma-separated list will clear the list on an
empty command.  So, if you wish to reset the rejection list specified in
global @{b}wgetrc@{ub}, you can do it with:

     reject =


@EndNode

@Node "Wgetrc Commands" "wget.guide/Wgetrc Commands"
@Next "Sample Wgetrc"
@Prev "Wgetrc Syntax"
@Toc "Startup File"

Wgetrc Commands
===============

   The complete set of commands is listed below, the letter after @{b}=@{ub}
denoting the value the command takes. It is @{b}on/off@{ub} for @{b}on@{ub} or @{b}off@{ub} (which
can also be @{b}1@{ub} or @{b}0@{ub}), STRING for any non-empty string or N for a
positive integer.  For example, you may specify @{b}use_proxy = off@{ub} to
disable use of @{i}proxy@{ui} servers by default. You may use @{b}inf@{ub} for infinite
values, where appropriate.

   Most of the commands have their equivalent command-line option (See
@{"Invoking" Link "Invoking"}), except some more obscure or rarely used ones.

accept/reject = STRING
     Same as @{b}-A@{ub}/@{b}-R@{ub} (See @{"Types of Files" Link "Types of Files"}).

add_hostdir = on/off
     Enable/disable host-prefixed file names. @{b}-nH@{ub} disables it.

always_rest = on/off
     Enable/disable continuation of the retrieval, the same as @{b}-c@{ub}.

base = STRING
     Set base for relative @{i}url@{ui}s, the same as @{b}-B@{ub}.

convert links = on/off
     Convert non-relative links locally. The same as @{b}-k@{ub}.

debug = on/off
     Debug mode, same as @{b}-d@{ub}.

delete_after = on/off
     Delete after download, the same as @{b}--delete-after@{ub}.

dir_mode = N
     Set permission modes of created subdirectories (default is 0755).

dir_prefix = STRING
     Top of directory tree, the same as @{b}-P@{ub}.

dirstruct = on/off
     Turning dirstruct on or off, the same as @{b}-x@{ub} or @{b}-nd@{ub}, respectively.

domains = STRING
     Same as @{b}-D@{ub} (See @{"Domain Acceptance" Link "Domain Acceptance"}).

dot_bytes = N
     Specify the number of bytes "contained" in a dot, as seen
     throughout the retrieval (1024 by default).  You can postfix the
     value with @{b}k@{ub} or @{b}m@{ub}, representing kilobytes and megabytes,
     respectively.  With dot settings you can tailor the dot retrieval
     to suit your needs, or you can use the predefined @{i}styles@{ui} (See
     @{"Advanced Options" Link "Advanced Options"}).

dots_in_line = N
     Specify the number of dots that will be printed in each line
     throughout the retrieval (50 by default).

dot_spacing = N
     Specify the number of dots in a single cluster (10 by default).

dot_style = STRING
     Specify the dot retrieval @{i}style@{ui}, as with @{b}--dot-style@{ub}.

exclude_directories = STRING
     Specify a comma-separated list of directories you wish to exclude
     from download, the same as @{b}-X@{ub} (See @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"}).

exclude_domains = STRING
     Same as @{b}--exclude-domains@{ub} (See @{"Domain Acceptance" Link "Domain Acceptance"}).

follow_ftp = on/off
     Follow @{i}ftp@{ui} links from @{i}html@{ui} documents, the same as @{b}-f@{ub}.

force_html = on/off
     If set to on, force the input filename to be regarded as an @{i}html@{ui}
     document, the same as @{b}-F@{ub}.

ftp_proxy = STRING
     Use STRING as @{i}ftp@{ui} proxy, instead of the one specified in
     environment.

glob = on/off
     Turn globbing on/off, the same as @{b}-g@{ub}.

header = STRING
     Define an additional header, like @{b}--header@{ub}.

http_passwd = STRING
     Set @{i}http@{ui} password.

http_proxy = STRING
     Use STRING as @{i}http@{ui} proxy, instead of the one specified in
     environment.

http_user = STRING
     Set @{i}http@{ui} user to STRING.

ignore_length = on/off
     When set to on, ignore @{b}Content-Length@{ub} header; the same as
     @{b}--ignore-length@{ub}.

include_directories = STRING
     Specify a comma-separated list of directories you wish to follow
     when downloading, the same as @{b}-I@{ub}.

input = STRING
     Read the @{i}url@{ui}s from STRING, like @{b}-i@{ub}.

kill_longer = on/off
     Consider data longer than specified in content-length header as
     invalid (and retry getting it). The default behaviour is to save
     as much data as there is, provided there is more than or equal to
     the value in @{b}Content-Length@{ub}.

logfile = STRING
     Set logfile, the same as @{b}-o@{ub}.

login = STRING
     Your user name on the remote machine, for @{i}ftp@{ui} Defaults to
     @{b}anonymous@{ub}.

mirror = on/off
     Turn mirroring on/off. The same as @{b}-m@{ub}.

noclobber = on/off
     Same as @{b}-nc@{ub}.

no_proxy = STRING
     Use STRING as the comma-separated list of domains to avoid in
     @{i}proxy@{ui} loading, instead of the one specified in
     environment.

no_parent = on/off
     Disallow retrieving outside the directory hierarchy, like
     @{b}--no-parent@{ub} (See @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"}).

output_document = STRING
     Set the output filename, the same as @{b}-O@{ub}.

passive_ftp = on/off
     Set passive @{i}ftp@{ui}, the same as @{b}--passive-ftp@{ub}.

passwd = STRING
     Set your @{i}ftp@{ui} password to PASSWORD.  Without this setting, the
     password defaults to @{b}username@hostname.domainname@{ub}.

proxy_user = STRING
     Set @{i}proxy@{ui} authentication user name to STRING, like @{b}--proxy-user@{ub}.

proxy_passwd = STRING
     Set @{i}proxy@{ui} authentication password to STRING, like @{b}--proxy-passwd@{ub}.

quiet = on/off
     Quiet mode, the same as @{b}-q@{ub}.

quota = QUOTA
     Specify the download quota, which is useful to put in global
     wgetrc. When download quota is specified, Wget will stop retrieving
     after the download sum has become greater than quota.  The quota
     can be specified in bytes (default), kbytes @{b}k@{ub} appended) or mbytes
     (@{b}m@{ub} appended).  Thus @{b}quota = 5m@{ub} will set the quota to 5 mbytes.
     Note that the user's startup file overrides system settings.

reclevel = N
     Recursion level, the same as @{b}-l@{ub}.

recursive = on/off
     Recursive on/off, the same as @{b}-r@{ub}.

relative_only = on/off
     Follow only relative links, the same as @{b}-L@{ub} (See @{"Relative Links" Link "Relative Links"}).

remove_listing = on/off
     If set to on, remove @{i}ftp@{ui} listings downloaded by Wget.  Setting it
     to off is the same as @{b}-nr@{ub}.

retr_symlinks = on/off
     When set to on, retrieve symbolic links as if they were plain
     files; the same as @{b}--retr-symlinks@{ub}.

robots = on/off
     Use (or not) @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file (See @{"Robots" Link "Robots"}).  Be sure to know what
     you are doing before changing the default (which is @{b}on@{ub}).

server_response = on/off
     Choose whether or not to print the @{i}http@{ui} and @{i}ftp@{ui} server responses,
     the same as @{b}-S@{ub}.

simple_host_check = on/off
     Same as @{b}-nh@{ub} (See @{"Host Checking" Link "Host Checking"}).

span_hosts = on/off
     Same as @{b}-H@{ub}.

timeout = N
     Set timeout value, the same as @{b}-T@{ub}.

timestamping = on/off
     Turn timestamping on/off. The same as @{b}-N@{ub} (See @{"Time-Stamping" Link "Time-Stamping"}).

tries = N
     Set number of retries per @{i}url@{ui}, the same as @{b}-t@{ub}.

use_proxy = on/off
     Turn @{i}proxy@{ui} support on/off. The same as @{b}-Y@{ub}.

verbose = on/off
     Turn verbose on/off, the same as @{b}-v@{ub}/@{b}-nv@{ub}.

wait = N
     Wait N seconds between retrievals, the same as @{b}-w@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Sample Wgetrc" "wget.guide/Sample Wgetrc"
@Prev "Wgetrc Commands"
@Toc "Startup File"

Sample Wgetrc
=============

   This is the sample initialization file, as given in the distribution.
It is divided in two section--one for global usage (suitable for global
startup file), and one for local usage (suitable for @{b}$HOME/.wgetrc@{ub}).
Be careful about the things you change.

   Note that all the lines are commented out.  For any line to have
effect, you must remove the @{b}#@{ub} prefix at the beginning of line.

     ###
     ### Sample Wget initialization file .wgetrc
     ###
     
     ## You can use this file to change the default behaviour of wget or to
     ## avoid having to type many many command-line options. This file does
     ## not contain a comprehensive list of commands -- look at the manual
     ## to find out what you can put into this file.
     ##
     ## Wget initialization file can reside in /usr/local/etc/wgetrc
     ## (global, for all users) or $HOME/.wgetrc (for a single user).
     ##
     ## To use any of the settings in this file, you will have to uncomment
     ## them (and probably change them).
     
     
     ##
     ## Global settings (useful for setting up in /usr/local/etc/wgetrc).
     ## Think well before you change them, since they may reduce wget's
     ## functionality, and make it behave contrary to the documentation:
     ##
     
     # You can set retrieve quota for beginners by specifying a value
     # optionally followed by 'K' (kilobytes) or 'M' (megabytes).  The
     # default quota is unlimited.
     #quota = inf
     
     # You can lower (or raise) the default number of retries when
     # downloading a file (default is 20).
     #tries = 20
     
     # Lowering the maximum depth of the recursive retrieval is handy to
     # prevent newbies from going too "deep" when they unwittingly start
     # the recursive retrieval.  The default is 5.
     #reclevel = 5
     
     # Many sites are behind firewalls that do not allow initiation of
     # connections from the outside.  On these sites you have to use the
     # `passive' feature of FTP.  If you are behind such a firewall, you
     # can turn this on to make Wget use passive FTP by default.
     #passive_ftp = off
     
     
     ##
     ## Local settings (for a user to set in his $HOME/.wgetrc).  It is
     ## *highly* undesirable to put these settings in the global file, since
     ## they are potentially dangerous to "normal" users.
     ##
     ## Even when setting up your own ~/.wgetrc, you should know what you
     ## are doing before doing so.
     ##
     
     # Set this to on to use timestamping by default:
     #timestamping = off
     
     # It is a good idea to make Wget send your email address in a `From:'
     # header with your request (so that server administrators can contact
     # you in case of errors).  Wget does *not* send `From:' by default.
     #header = From: Your Name <username@site.domain>
     
     # You can set up other headers, like Accept-Language.  Accept-Language
     # is *not* sent by default.
     #header = Accept-Language: en
     
     # You can set the default proxy for Wget to use.  It will override the
     # value in the environment.
     #http_proxy = http://proxy.yoyodyne.com:18023/
     
     # If you do not want to use proxy at all, set this to off.
     #use_proxy = on
     
     # You can customize the retrieval outlook.  Valid options are default,
     # binary, mega and micro.
     #dot_style = default
     
     # Setting this to off makes Wget not download /robots.txt.  Be sure to
     # know *exactly* what /robots.txt is and how it is used before changing
     # the default!
     #robots = on
     
     # It can be useful to make Wget wait between connections.  Set this to
     # the number of seconds you want Wget to wait.
     #wait = 0
     
     # You can force creating directory structure, even if a single is being
     # retrieved, by setting this to on.
     #dirstruct = off
     
     # You can turn on recursive retrieving by default (don't do this if
     # you are not sure you know what it means) by setting this to on.
     #recursive = off
     
     # To have Wget follow FTP links from HTML files by default, set this
     # to on:
     #follow_ftp = off


@EndNode

@Node "Examples" "wget.guide/Examples"
@Next "Various"
@Prev "Startup File"
@Toc "Main"

Examples
********

   The examples are classified into three sections, because of clarity.
The first section is a tutorial for beginners.  The second section
explains some of the more complex program features.  The third section
contains advice for mirror administrators, as well as even more complex
features (that some would call perverted).


 @{" Simple Usage              " Link "Simple Usage"}  Simple, basic usage of the program.
 @{" Advanced Usage            " Link "Advanced Usage"}  Advanced techniques of usage.
 @{" Guru Usage                " Link "Guru Usage"}  Mirroring and the hairy stuff.


@EndNode

@Node "Simple Usage" "wget.guide/Simple Usage"
@Next "Advanced Usage"
@Prev "Examples"
@Toc "Examples"

Simple Usage
============

   @{b}*@{ub} Say you want to download a @{i}url@{ui}.  Just type:

          wget http://fly.cc.fer.hr/

     The response will be something like:

          --13:30:45--  http://fly.cc.fer.hr:80/
                     => `index.html'
          Connecting to fly.cc.fer.hr:80... connected!
          HTTP request sent, fetching headers... done.
          Length: 1,749 [text/html]
          
              0K -> .
          
          13:30:46 (68.32K/s) - `index.html' saved [1749/1749]

   @{b}*@{ub} But what will happen if the connection is slow, and the file is
     lengthy?  The connection will probably fail before the whole file
     is retrieved, more than once.  In this case, Wget will try getting
     the file until it either gets the whole of it, or exceeds the
     default number of retries (this being 20).  It is easy to change
     the number of tries to 45, to insure that the whole file will
     arrive safely:

          wget --tries=45 http://fly.cc.fer.hr/jpg/flyweb.jpg

   @{b}*@{ub} Now let's leave Wget to work in the background, and write its
     progress to log file @{b}log@{ub}.  It is tiring to type @{b}--tries@{ub}, so we
     shall use @{b}-t@{ub}.

          wget -t 45 -o log http://fly.cc.fer.hr/jpg/flyweb.jpg &

     The ampersand at the end of the line makes sure that Wget works in
     the background.  To unlimit the number of retries, use @{b}-t inf@{ub}.

   @{b}*@{ub} The usage of @{i}ftp@{ui} is as simple.  Wget will take care of login and
     password.

          $ wget ftp://gnjilux.cc.fer.hr/welcome.msg
          --23:35:55--  ftp://gnjilux.cc.fer.hr:21/welcome.msg
                     => `welcome.msg'
          Connecting to gnjilux.cc.fer.hr:21... connected!
          Logging in as anonymous ... Logged in!
          ==> TYPE I ... done.  ==> CWD not needed.
          ==> PORT ... done.    ==> RETR welcome.msg ... done.
          Length: 1,340 (unauthoritative)
          
              0K -> .
          
          23:35:56 (37.39K/s) - `welcome.msg' saved [1340]

   @{b}*@{ub} If you specify a directory, Wget will retrieve the directory
     listing, parse it and convert it to @{i}html@{ui}.  Try:

          wget ftp://prep.ai.mit.edu/pub/gnu/
          lynx index.html


@EndNode

@Node "Advanced Usage" "wget.guide/Advanced Usage"
@Next "Guru Usage"
@Prev "Simple Usage"
@Toc "Examples"

Advanced Usage
==============

   @{b}*@{ub} You would like to read the list of @{i}url@{ui}s from a file?  Not a problem
     with that:

          wget -i file

     If you specify @{b}-@{ub} as file name, the @{i}url@{ui}s will be read from standard
     input.

   @{b}*@{ub} Create a mirror image of GNU @{i}www@{ui} site (with the same directory
     structure the original has) with only one try per document, saving
     the log of the activities to @{b}gnulog@{ub}:

          wget -r -t1 http://www.gnu.ai.mit.edu/ -o gnulog

   @{b}*@{ub} Retrieve the first layer of yahoo links:

          wget -r -l1 http://www.yahoo.com/

   @{b}*@{ub} Retrieve the index.html of @{b}www.lycos.com@{ub}, showing the original
     server headers:

          wget -S http://www.lycos.com/

   @{b}*@{ub} Save the server headers with the file:
          wget -s http://www.lycos.com/
          more index.html

   @{b}*@{ub} Retrieve the first two levels of @{b}wuarchive.wustl.edu@{ub}, saving them
     to /tmp.

          wget -P/tmp -l2 ftp://wuarchive.wustl.edu/

   @{b}*@{ub} You want to download all the @{i}gif@{ui}s from an @{i}http@{ui} directory.  @{b}wget
     http://host/dir/*.gif@{ub} doesn't work, since @{i}http@{ui} retrieval does not
     support globbing.  In that case, use:

          wget -r -l1 --no-parent -A.gif http://host/dir/

     It is a bit of a kludge, but it works perfectly.  @{b}-r -l1@{ub} means to
     retrieve recursively (See @{"Advanced Options" Link "Advanced Options"}), with maximum depth of
     1.  @{b}--no-parent@{ub} means that references to the parent directory are
     ignored (See @{"Directory-Based Limits" Link "Directory-Based Limits"}), and @{b}-A.gif@{ub} means to download
     only the @{i}gif@{ui} files.  @{b}-A "*.gif"@{ub} would have worked too.

   @{b}*@{ub} Suppose you were in the middle of downloading, when Wget was
     interrupted.  Now you do not want to clobber the files already
     present.  It would be:

          wget -nc -r http://www.gnu.ai.mit.edu/

   @{b}*@{ub} If you want to encode your own username and password to @{i}http@{ui} or
     @{i}ftp@{ui}, use the appropriate @{i}url@{ui} syntax (See @{"URL Format" Link "URL Format"}).

          wget ftp://hniksic:mypassword@jagor.srce.hr/.emacs

   @{b}*@{ub} If you do not like the default retrieval visualization (1K dots
     with 10 dots per cluster and 50 dots per line), you can customize
     it through dot settings (See @{"Wgetrc Commands" Link "Wgetrc Commands"}).  For example, many
     people like the "binary" style of retrieval, with 8K dots and 512K
     lines:

          wget --dot-style=binary ftp://prep.ai.mit.edu/pub/gnu/README

     You can experiment with other styles, like:

          wget --dot-style=mega ftp://ftp.xemacs.org/pub/xemacs/xemacs-19.15.tar.gz
          wget --dot-style=micro http://fly.cc.fer.hr/

     To make these settings permanent, put them in your @{b}.wgetrc@{ub}, as
     described before (See @{"Sample Wgetrc" Link "Sample Wgetrc"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Guru Usage" "wget.guide/Guru Usage"
@Prev "Advanced Usage"
@Toc "Examples"

Guru Usage
==========

   @{b}*@{ub} If you wish Wget to keep a mirror of a page (or @{i}ftp@{ui}
     subdirectories), use @{b}--mirror@{ub} (@{b}-m@{ub}), which is the shorthand for @{b}-r
     -N@{ub}.  You can put Wget in the crontab file asking it to recheck a
     site each Sunday:

          crontab
          0 0 * * 0 wget --mirror ftp://ftp.xemacs.org/pub/xemacs/ -o /home/me/weeklog

   @{b}*@{ub} You may wish to do the same with someone's home page.  But you do
     not want to download all those images--you're only interested in
     @{i}html@{ui}.

          wget --mirror -A.html http://www.w3.org/

   @{b}*@{ub} But what about mirroring the hosts networkologically close to you?
     It seems so awfully slow because of all that @{i}dns@{ui} resolving.  Just
     use @{b}-D@{ub} (See @{"Domain Acceptance" Link "Domain Acceptance"}).

          wget -rN -Dsrce.hr http://www.srce.hr/

     Now Wget will correctly find out that @{b}regoc.srce.hr@{ub} is the same as
     @{b}www.srce.hr@{ub}, but will not even take into consideration the
     link to @{b}www.mit.edu@{ub}.

   @{b}*@{ub} You have a presentation and would like the dumb absolute links to
     be converted to relative?  Use @{b}-k@{ub}:

          wget -k -r URL

   @{b}*@{ub} You would like the output documents to go to standard output
     instead of to files?  OK, but Wget will automatically shut up
     (turn on @{b}--quiet@{ub}) to prevent mixing of Wget output and the
     retrieved documents.

          wget -O - http://jagor.srce.hr/ http://www.srce.hr/

     You can also combine the two options and make weird pipelines to
     retrieve the documents from remote hotlists:

          wget -O - http://cool.list.com/ | wget --force-html -i -


@EndNode

