@Node "Distribution" "wget.guide/Distribution"
@Next "Mailing List"
@Prev "Various"
@Toc "Various"

Distribution
============

   Like all GNU utilities, the latest version of Wget can be found at
the master GNU archive site prep.ai.mit.edu, and its mirrors.  For
example, Wget 1.4.5 is at:

     <URL:ftp://prep.ai.mit.edu/pub/gnu/wget-1.4.5.tar.gz>.

   The latest version is also available via FTP from the maintainer's
machine, at:

     <URL:ftp://gnjilux.cc.fer.hr/pub/unix/util/wget/wget.tar.gz>.

   This location is mirrored at:

     <URL:ftp://sunsite.auc.dk/pub/infosystems/wget/> and
     <URL:http://sunsite.auc.dk/ftp/pub/infosystems/wget/>.
     <URL:ftp://ftp.fu-berlin.de/pub/unix/network/wget/>

   I'll try to make a "real" home page for Wget some time in the future.
If you would like to do it, please say so--I'll be delighted.


@EndNode

@Node "Mailing List" "wget.guide/Mailing List"
@Next "Reporting Bugs"
@Prev "Distribution"
@Toc "Various"

Mailing List
============

   Wget has its own mailing list at @{b}<wget@sunsite.auc.dk>@{ub}, thanks to
Karsten Thygesen.  The mailing list is for discussion of Wget features
and web, reporting Wget bugs (those that you think may be of interest
to the public) and mailing announcements.  You are welcome to
subscribe.  The more people on the list, the better!

   To subscribe, send mail to @{b}<wget-request@sunsite.auc.dk>@{ub} with the
magic word @{b}subscribe@{ub} in the subject line.  Unsubscribe analogously.

   The mailing list is archived at
@{b}http://fly.cc.fer.hr/en/wget-archive.mbox@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Reporting Bugs" "wget.guide/Reporting Bugs"
@Next "Portability"
@Prev "Mailing List"
@Toc "Various"

Reporting Bugs
==============

   You are welcome to send bug reports about GNU Wget to
@{b}<bug-wget@prep.ai.mit.edu>@{ub}.  The bugs that you think are of the
interest to the public (i.e. more people should be informed about them)
can be Cc-ed to the mailing list at @{b}<wget@sunsite.auc.dk>@{ub}.

   Before actually submitting a bug report, please try to follow a few
simple guidelines.

  1. Please try to ascertain that the behaviour you see really is a
     bug.  If Wget crashes, it's a bug.  If Wget does not behave as
     documented, it's a bug.  If things work strange, but you are not
     sure about the way they are supposed to work, it might well be a
     bug.

  2. Try to repeat the bug in as simple circumstances as possible.
     E.g. if Wget crashes on @{b}wget -rLl0 -t5 -Y0 http://yoyodyne.com -o
     /tmp/log@{ub}, you should try to see if it will crash with a simpler
     set of options.

  3. Please start Wget with @{b}-d@{ub} option and send the log (or the relevant
     parts of it).  If Wget was compiled without debug support,
     recompile it.  It is @{i}much@{ui} easier to trace bugs with debug support
     on.

  4. If Wget has crashed, try to run it in a debugger, e.g. @{b}gdb `which
     wget` core@{ub} and type @{b}where@{ub} to get the backtrace.

  5. Find where the bug is, fix it and send me the patches. :-)


@EndNode

@Node "Portability" "wget.guide/Portability"
@Next "Signals"
@Prev "Reporting Bugs"
@Toc "Various"

Portability
===========

   Since Wget uses GNU Autoconf for building and configuring, and avoids
using "special" features of any one Unix system, it should compile (and
work) on all common flavors of Unix.

   This version was compiled and tested this version on various Unix
systems, including Solaris, Linux, SunOS, OSF (aka Digital Unix), and
Ultrix; refer to the file @{b}MACHINES@{ub} in the distribution directory for a
comprehensive list.  If you compile it on an architecture not listed
there, please let me know.

   Wget should also compile on the other Unix systems, not listed in
@{b}MACHINES@{ub}.  If it doesn't, please let me know.


@EndNode

@Node "Signals" "wget.guide/Signals"
@Prev "Portability"
@Toc "Various"

Signals
=======

   Since the purpose of Wget is background work, it catches the hangup
signal (@{b}SIGHUP@{ub}) and ignores it.  If the output was on standard output,
it will be redirected to a file named @{b}wget-log@{ub}.  Otherwise, @{b}SIGHUP@{ub} is
ignored.  This is convenient when you wish to redirect the output of
Wget after having started it.

     $ wget http://www.ifi.uio.no/~larsi/gnus.tar.gz &
     $ kill -HUP %%     # Redirect the output to wget-log

   Other than that, Wget will not try to interfere with signals in any
way. @{b}C-c@{ub}, @{b}kill -TERM@{ub} and @{b}kill -KILL@{ub} should kill it alike.


@EndNode

@Node "Appendices" "wget.guide/Appendices"
@Next "Copying"
@Prev "Various"
@Toc "Main"

Appendices
**********

   This chapter contains some references I consider useful, like the
Robots Exclusion Standard specification, as well as a list of
contributors to GNU Wget.


 @{" Robots                    " Link "Robots"}  Wget as a WWW robot.
 @{" Security Considerations   " Link "Security Considerations"}  Security with Wget.
 @{" Contributors              " Link "Contributors"}  People who helped.


@EndNode

@Node "Robots" "wget.guide/Robots"
@Next "Security Considerations"
@Prev "Appendices"
@Toc "Appendices"

Robots
======

   Since Wget is able to traverse the web, it counts as one of the Web
@{i}robots@{ui}.  Thus Wget understands @{i}Robots Exclusion Standard@{ui}
(@{i}res@{ui})--contents of @{b}/robots.txt@{ub}, used by server administrators
to shield parts of their systems from wanderings of Wget.

   Norobots support is turned on only when retrieving recursively, and
@{i}never@{ui} for the first page.  Thus, you may issue:

     wget -r http://fly.cc.fer.hr/

   First the index of fly.cc.fer.hr will be downloaded.  If Wget finds
anything worth downloading on the same host, only @{i}then@{ui} will it load the
robots, and decide whether or not to load the links after all.
@{b}/robots.txt@{ub} is loaded only once per host.  Wget does not support
the robots @{b}META@{ub} tag.

   The description of the norobots standard was written, and is
maintained by Martijn Koster @{b}<m.koster@webcrawler.com>@{ub}.  With his
permission, I contribute a (slightly modified) texified version of the
@{i}res@{ui}.


 @{" Introduction to RES       " Link "Introduction to RES"}  
 @{" RES Format                " Link "RES Format"}  
 @{" User-Agent Field          " Link "User-Agent Field"}  
 @{" Disallow Field            " Link "Disallow Field"}  
 @{" Norobots Examples         " Link "Norobots Examples"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Introduction to RES" "wget.guide/Introduction to RES"
@Next "RES Format"
@Prev "Robots"
@Toc "Robots"

Introduction to RES
-------------------

   @{i}WWW Robots@{ui} (also called @{i}wanderers@{ui} or @{i}spiders@{ui}) are programs that
traverse many pages in the World Wide Web by recursively retrieving
linked pages. For more information see the robots page.

   In 1993 and 1994 there have been occasions where robots have visited
@{i}www@{ui} servers where they weren't welcome for various reasons.
Sometimes these reasons were robot specific, e.g. certain robots
swamped servers with rapid-fire requests, or retrieved the same files
repeatedly. In other situations robots traversed parts of @{i}www@{ui} servers
that weren't suitable, e.g. very deep virtual trees, duplicated
information, temporary information, or cgi-scripts with side-effects
(such as voting).

   These incidents indicated the need for established mechanisms for
@{i}www@{ui} servers to indicate to robots which parts of their server
should not be accessed. This standard addresses this need with an
operational solution.

   This document represents a consensus on 30 June 1994 on the robots
mailing list (@{b}robots@webcrawler.com@{ub}), between the majority of robot
authors and other people with an interest in robots. It has also been
open for discussion on the Technical World Wide Web mailing list
(@{b}www-talk@info.cern.ch@{ub}). This document is based on a previous
working draft under the same title.

   It is not an official standard backed by a standards body, or owned
by any commercial organization. It is not enforced by anybody, and there
no guarantee that all current and future robots will use it. Consider
it a common facility the majority of robot authors offer the @{i}www@{ui}
community to protect @{i}www@{ui} server against unwanted accesses by their
robots.

   The latest version of this document can be found at:

     http://info.webcrawler.com/mak/projects/robots/norobots.html


@EndNode

@Node "RES Format" "wget.guide/RES Format"
@Next "User-Agent Field"
@Prev "Introduction to RES"
@Toc "Robots"

RES Format
----------

   The format and semantics of the @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file are as follows:

   The file consists of one or more records separated by one or more
blank lines (terminated by @{b}CR@{ub}, @{b}CR/NL@{ub}, or @{b}NL@{ub}).  Each record contains
lines of the form:

     <field>:<optionalspace><value><optionalspace>

   The field name is case insensitive.

   Comments can be included in file using UNIX bourne shell conventions:
the @{b}#@{ub} character is used to indicate that preceding space (if any) and
the remainder of the line up to the line termination is discarded.
Lines containing only a comment are discarded completely, and therefore
do not indicate a record boundary.

   The record starts with one or more User-agent lines, followed by one
or more Disallow lines, as detailed below. Unrecognized headers are
ignored.

   The presence of an empty @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file has no explicit associated
semantics, it will be treated as if it was not present, i.e. all robots
will consider themselves welcome.


@EndNode

@Node "User-Agent Field" "wget.guide/User-Agent Field"
@Next "Disallow Field"
@Prev "RES Format"
@Toc "Robots"

User-Agent Field
----------------

   The value of this field is the name of the robot the record is
describing access policy for.

   If more than one User-agent field is present the record describes an
identical access policy for more than one robot.  At least one field
needs to be present per record.

   The robot should be liberal in interpreting this field. A case
insensitive substring match of the name without version information is
recommended.

   If the value is @{b}*@{ub}, the record describes the default access policy
for any robot that has not matched any of the other records. It is not
allowed to have multiple such records in the @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file.


@EndNode

@Node "Disallow Field" "wget.guide/Disallow Field"
@Next "Norobots Examples"
@Prev "User-Agent Field"
@Toc "Robots"

Disallow Field
--------------

   The value of this field specifies a partial @{i}url@{ui} that is not to be
visited. This can be a full path, or a partial path; any @{i}url@{ui} that
starts with this value will not be retrieved. For example,
@{b}Disallow: /help@{ub} disallows both @{b}/help.html@{ub} and @{b}/help/index.html@{ub},
whereas @{b}Disallow: /help/@{ub} would disallow @{b}/help/index.html@{ub} but allow
@{b}/help.html@{ub}.

   Any empty value, indicates that all @{i}url@{ui}s can be retrieved. At least
one Disallow field needs to be present in a record.


@EndNode

@Node "Norobots Examples" "wget.guide/Norobots Examples"
@Prev "Disallow Field"
@Toc "Robots"

Norobots Examples
-----------------

   The following example @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file specifies that no robots
should visit any @{i}url@{ui} starting with @{b}/cyberworld/map/@{ub} or @{b}/tmp/@{ub}:

     # robots.txt for http://www.site.com/
     
     User-agent: *
     Disallow: /cyberworld/map/ # This is an infinite virtual URL space
     Disallow: /tmp/ # these will soon disappear

   This example @{b}/robots.txt@{ub} file specifies that no robots should visit
any @{i}url@{ui} starting with @{b}/cyberworld/map/@{ub}, except the robot called
@{b}cybermapper@{ub}:

     # robots.txt for http://www.site.com/
     
     User-agent: *
     Disallow: /cyberworld/map/ # This is an infinite virtual URL space
     
     # Cybermapper knows where to go.
     User-agent: cybermapper
     Disallow:

   This example indicates that no robots should visit this site further:

     # go away
     User-agent: *
     Disallow: /


@EndNode

@Node "Security Considerations" "wget.guide/Security Considerations"
@Next "Contributors"
@Prev "Robots"
@Toc "Appendices"

Security Considerations
=======================

   When using Wget, you must be aware that it is sends unencrypted
passwords through the network, which may present a security problem.
Here are the main issues, and some solutions.

  1. The passwords on the command line are visible using @{b}ps@{ub}.  If this
     is a problem, avoid putting passwords from the command line--e.g.
     you can use @{b}.netrc@{ub} for this.

  2. Only the insecure @{i}basic@{ui} authentication scheme is supported in
     @{i}http@{ui}, which also sends unencrypted passwords through the
     network all routers and gateways.  Feel free to implement
     something better.

  3. The @{i}ftp@{ui} passwords are also in no way encrypted.  There is no good
     solution for this at the moment.

  4. Although the "normal" output of Wget tries to hide the passwords,
     debugging logs show them, in all forms.  This problem is avoided by
     being careful when you send debug logs (yes, even when you send
     them to me).


@EndNode

@Node "Contributors" "wget.guide/Contributors"
@Prev "Security Considerations"
@Toc "Appendices"

Contributors
============

   GNU Wget was written by Hrvoje Niksic @{b}<hniksic@srce.hr>@{ub}.  However,
its development could never have gone as far as it has, were it not for
the help of many people, either with bug reports, feature proposals,
patches, or letters saying "Thanks!".

   Special thanks goes to the following people (no particular order):

   @{b}*@{ub} Karsten Thygesen--donated @{i}ftp@{ui} space and mailing list.

   @{b}*@{ub} Shawn McHorse--bug reports and patches.

   @{b}*@{ub} Kaveh R. Ghazi--on-the-fly ansi2knr-ization.

   @{b}*@{ub} Gordon Matzigkeit--@{b}.netrc@{ub} support.

   @{b}*@{ub} Zlatko Calusic, Drazen Kacar--feature suggestions and
     "philosophical" discussions.

   @{b}*@{ub} Darko Budor--port to Windows.

   @{b}*@{ub} Antonio Rosella--help and suggestions.

   @{b}*@{ub} Tomislav Petrovic, Mario Mikocevic--many bug reports and
     suggestions.

   The following people have either provided bug reports, useful
suggestoins, or beta tested the various releases:

   Dieter Baron, Roger Beeman, Mark Boyns, Kristijan Conkas, Damir
Dzeko, Andrew Davison, Marc Duponcheel, Aleksandar Erkalovic, Gregor
Hoffleit, Erik Magnus Hulthen, Richard Huveneers, Mario Juric, Goran
Kezunovic, Martin Kraemer, Tage Stabell-Kulo, Hrvoje Lacko, Francois
Pinard, Andrew Pollock, Steve Pothier, Sven Sternberger, Markus
Strasser, Russell Vincent, Tomislav Vujec, Jasmin Zainul, Bojan Zdrnja,
Kristijan Zimmer.

   I apologize to all whom I forgot to mention (probably a lot).  Also
thanks to all the subscribers of the Wget mailing list.


@EndNode

